[2] Personal protective equipment
Date: Tue 24 Oct 2017 07:00 EAT
Source: L'Express Madagascar [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://goo.gl/HJJMxK


A total of 30 health care students have contracted plague by intervening in the management of patients, since the beginning of the epidemic. The announcement was made by Hery Perez De Cuellar, president of the National Association of Interns inside the University Hospital Joseph Ravoahangy Andrianavalona (CHU JRA) yesterday, 23 Oct 2017. "We are weakly protected in the care of patients. The mouth covers used are those used by surgeons. The on-call blouses change only every 24 hours. And at the beginning of the epidemic, we bought ourselves this equipment," said the medical student, shocked.

These 7th and 8th year students of the Faculty of Medicine are an integral part of health personnel involved in the care of plague victims. "We receive the patients at the triage, do the tubing or the puncture for the rapid diagnostic test, and inject the patients. Sometimes we take samples from a corpse. So we are exposed to the bacteria at any time," testified these future doctors. The majority of these students are already healed, and some are still undergoing treatment. Others are on contact chemoprophylaxis.

These interns threaten to suspend their activities, if they do not have personal protective equipment. "We are not going to expose our lives to such a danger, however, knowing that other health workers receive more appropriate protection," they say.

The Ministry of Public Health denies this information. "They exaggerate. The delivery of equipment has been slightly delayed, but that's it; it arrived and was given to beneficiaries this afternoon (note: yesterday)," says a source from the ministry.

These students are not the only [healthcare] victims of this disease since the beginning of the epidemic. In 2 months, at least 2 dozen doctors, paramedics, and other health workers, have been affected and were cured.

